  {
    "id": "1muwsfr",
    "title": "Anna Nicole Smith 26 with billionaire J. Howard Marshall 89 in 1994 just after their  marriage After he died a year later, his $1.6 billion estate went entirely to his son. Despite years of legal battles, Anna never received a penny.",
    "description": "Anna Nicole Smith married billionaire J. Howard Marshall in 1994 when he was 89 and she was 26. After he died a year later, his $1.6 billion estate went entirely to his son. Despite years of legal battles, Anna never received a penny.",
    "imageUrl": "/photos/1muwsfr.jpeg",
    "postedAt": "2025-08-19",
    "upvotes": 29273,
    "year": "1994",
    "comments": [
      {
        "id": "n9m9ba2",
        "author": "[已删除]",
        "score": 1315,
        "body": null,
        "replies": [
          {
            "id": "n9n62sh",
            "author": "cleanpapertiger",
            "score": 531,
            "body": "Wait, so she was only asking for $100 million of the 1.6 billion, not the whole amount?  \nEven if the son was sure she was a gold digger, $100 million isn't much to make her go away, in the grand scheme of it.",
            "replies": [
              {
                "id": "n9pq61s",
                "author": "Imagination_Theory",
                "score": 412,
                "body": "It was half of his estate that Anna Nicole Smith said he promised her. And I believe her. She was awarded $449 million by the bankruptcy court. That judgment was later vacated and Smith’s award was reduced to $88 million. And then that judgement was also later vacated. \n \n\nSmith and J. Howard III (Marshall's other son who was left out of any will and trust) went to court together to fight for a piece of the estate. \n\n \nPierce (the son that was awarded everything in the will) and Anna Nicole Smith were suing, counter suing and going to many different court cases for 20 years with both winning their cases, eventually it had to go up to federal court and then eventually it ended up at the US Supreme Court in Marshall v. Marshall and Stern v. Marshall. \n\nI don't fault Pierce or Anna Nicole Smith for doing what they did, or the other brother. They all had very normal and common reactions. Most people in any one of their shoes would react the same way they did. \n\nThe villain of the story is the father who took one son out of his will (and over something super petty), the father who was cheating on Peirce's mother (the brothers had different mothers) while she had alzheimer's and was planning on marrying different strippers after his wife died and was putting different strippers on his payroll as \"consultants\"\nand the man who went after a 26 year old with a child when he was 90 something and made many promises to her and then lied to her. They had a deal and she fulfilled that deal. He didn't. He did purposely leave her out of the will, just like he did with his other son. \n\nJ. Howard Marshall the second was the problem in all of their lives. He should have just made a proper will and given them each something. Instead he created more suffering for them even in his death.",
                "replies": [
                  {
                    "id": "n9py0jb",
                    "author": "BlankBlankblackBlank",
                    "score": 154,
                    "body": "I actually think this is the perfect take. They were all screwed over.",
                    "replies": [
                      {
                        "id": "n9q4kip",
                        "author": "Aggravating-Smoke848",
                        "score": 70,
                        "body": "And there was PLENTY of money to ensure everyone was taken care of .",
                        "replies": []
                      },
                      {
                        "id": "n9whmgf",
                        "author": "RevolutionaryHair91",
                        "score": 11,
                        "body": "You don't get to have 1.6 billion without having a nature to screw everyone over whenever you can. It's a built in feature that gets you there. The fact he screwed his own family and after his death is just what makes it stand out but it's perfectly in line with whatever got in there in the first place.",
                        "replies": []
                      },
                      {
                        "id": "n9x8w7z",
                        "author": "TheSmartGuyTJ",
                        "score": 4,
                        "body": "I think leaving mass fortunes in your will at such an old age is the ultimately the most selfish and egotistical move ever and envitably will end up in court battles just like this.\n\nWhen you start hitting the high numbers start dividing up your assets, otherwise case in point will ensue.",
                        "replies": []
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "n9pyfwy",
                    "author": "cuntyhuntyslaymama",
                    "score": 26,
                    "body": "Wish I could make everyone in this thread read this comment, thank you",
                    "replies": []
                  },
                  {
