                "id": "n9pid23",
                "author": "questionsaboutrel521",
                "score": 17,
                "body": "There’s a reason that it was so hotly contested legally. There’s a ton of claims and counterclaims by both sides and it involves so many different areas of law - bankruptcy, libel, trusts, probate, family law, elder abuse, legal jurisdiction. It’s actually an incredibly fascinating issue and resulted in two Supreme Court cases. \n\nWhat is interesting about Pierce Marshall is that he ignored what would be smart legal advice - to reach out to the petitioner and settle. Probably for a relatively small sum, given the size of the estate, he could have had her sign that she would give up all claims. Instead, he chose to fight this *past the point of his own death* and considering that this stretched into multiple state and federal courts for a dozen years, I would venture it was not worth the time, stress, and money spent.",
                "replies": [
                  {
                    "id": "n9q7ve7",
                    "author": "Kneef",
                    "score": 3,
                    "body": "Pettiness and greed.",
                    "replies": []
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "id": "n9q3oa5",
                "author": "MessiComeLately",
                "score": 4,
                "body": "After dealing with my elderly mother for a few years, I have my doubts about this. There are things she agrees she needs to do to make things simpler for my sister and me when she dies. It doesn't affect who gets what, just how quickly and easily we get it when she dies, and she understands it because she went through the process when my father died. Most things passed to her simply and easily, but a few things that he overlooked went through probate, which was an enormous pain in the ass for her. Because of that, she's determined to make everything easy for her children.\n\nHowever, she is no longer capable of managing her own performance of this task. She doesn't feel any sense of discomfort with the fact that years have passed without any progress. She has complete confidence that with her current approach she's going to get it done any day now, most likely next week. She has the same comfort in the imminent completion of the work as she did last year, the year before, and the year before.\n\nI can imagine poor Anna Nicole Smith sucking this old guy's dick for an entire year hoping for that hundred million dollars, and him sincerely intending to give it to her, and he just doesn't get it done. Not because he's stringing her along with false promises but because he doesn't feel time passing anymore. If that's what happened, I feel sorry for her.\n\nAlso, I wonder what was going with the son that he didn't let her have even a fraction of the estate. Wouldn't he be grateful that his dad got to spend his last year over the moon for a beautiful young girl? I'm surprised he didn't offer some kind of settlement that would have set her up for life.",
                "replies": []
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
