                        "id": "n9n1vfj",
                        "author": "[已删除]",
                        "score": 12,
                        "body": "The courts could not rule that he wasn't well enough to sign the paperwork, but it was still binding. They had to have ruled that he was in fact, well enough to sign the paperwork at the time he signed it, even if you personally disagree with the court. Who sued the buyer on his behalf after the sale?",
                        "replies": [
                          {
                            "id": "n9n2hsc",
                            "author": "LordGwyn-n-Tonic",
                            "score": 11,
                            "body": "My grandmother. Basically, as I love in another state and wasn't around when it happened, I was told: the Judge essentially said that the burden was on my grandmother and their sons to make sure he wasn't doing this kind of thing if they knew he was like this. \n\nFull disclosure, I've been telling my dad for almost a decade that he had some sort of dementia and they needed to get him checked out, but was always told that's just what happens when you get his age. So like, I will admit they buried their heads in the sand about it and let him drive around and preach even though he was going to visit people who had been dead for decades or would ask how someone was doing three times over the course of five minutes.",
